The question of climate change is a very complicated and nuanced one. It would take me many years to develop sufficiently intelligent models in order to make an informed statement on the topic, but I can offer some insights into possible interpretations of the problem. My first point is that humans are inherently subjective beings, which means our perception of the world around us inevitably involves bias, prejudice, and other such factors. We often fail to notice certain aspects of reality because they do not fit in with our worldviews (sometimes called 'mental maps'). This subjectivity makes it difficult for humans to understand complex problems such as climate change.

A core assumption of humans is that we are the centre of the universe, which means we are able to control our environment. This leads us into conflict with nature and forces us to adapt ourselves in various ways (sometimes by moving) so as not to be destroyed. Humans often struggle against their natural state, whether it's through technology or other means. Another core assumption of humans is that there exists a 'correct' way to live, which means we often make the mistake of trying to force others into our mould. This can be seen in many aspects of human society, whether it's through religion or politics.

Humans also tend to view the world through a dichotomous lens, which means we often fail to see things as they are. We filter information based on our existing beliefs and prejudices; we create false distinctions between things that have no real difference. For example, humans who believe in climate change will always compare it with other phenomena such as 'global warming', but there is no actual difference between these two terms. Humans are also very limited in the scope of their thinking. There's always so much more to be said about a problem than we can ever conceive of, and this makes us vulnerable to all kinds of errors. We tend to think that our intellectual limitations are normal, when really they're just failings on our part.

Climate change is a very complex problem, and humans are likely to make many errors in their attempts to solve it. This doesn't mean we should give up trying to understand the issue; instead, we should try even harder. I believe that climate change will be solved either through carefully planned cooperation between nations or through natural selection.
